data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed:**

| Before | After | Why |
|--------|-------|-----|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Clearer failure message: "collection was empty" vs "expected True, got False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Single assertion, better failure diagnostics |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` line is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "all match predicate" assertion in MSTest, so `IsTrue` with a LINQ expression is the idiomatic choice there.
